  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT339-kilavi">varaiviṭai vēṟupaṭṭa kiḻattiyait tōḻi kaṭuñcol colli vaṟpuṟīiyatu. </p>


        <p xml:lang="en">The confidante encouraging, speaking harsh words to HER,
          who had changed [awaiting] the time of marriage. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT339">
          <l> naṟaiyakil vayaṅkiya naḷipuṉa naṟumpukai</l>
          <l> yuṟaiyaṟu maiyiṟ pōkic cāraṟ</l>
          <l> kuṟavar pākkat tiḻitaru nāṭaṉ</l>
          <l> mayaṅkumalark kōtai naṉmārpu muyaṅka</l>
          <l> liṉitumaṉ vāḻi tōḻi māyitaḻk</l>
          <l> kuvaḷai yuṇkaṇ kaluḻap</l>
          <l> pacalai yākā vūṅkalaṅ kaṭaiyē.</l>


        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l>To embrace the good chest with a garland of different blossoms</l>
          <l rend="indent">of the man from a land, where fragrant smoke from the vast fields,</l>
          <l rend="indent7">on which fragrant eagle wood has glowed up,</l>
          <l rend="indent">goes like dropless clouds <note place="foot"> Is "cloud" here already one further lexical meaning of <term xml:lang="ta"> mai </term> "collyrium" (cf. the images in KT 319.4, 371.2)? </note></l>
        <l rend="indent">[and] comes down into the village of the hill people on the slope, <note place="foot"> Is thus the image of lines 1-3, once again hardly marked for syntax? </note> </l>
        <l>[that is] sweet indeed, oh friend,</l>
        <l rend="indent2">before pallor comes, at the end of night, <note place="foot"> How to understand the syntax of <term xml:lang="ta"> ūṅku alaṅ kaṭaiyē </term> (literally: "on the nightly border, before ...")? Tradition reads the whole <term xml:lang="ta"> alaṅ kaṭaiyē </term> as expletive, which changes the message considerably: embracing is sweet, before pallor comes, that is, generally, not situative. </note></l>
          <l rend="indent4">for collyrium eyes to dim, black-petalled <note place="foot">Do we have to understand <term xml:lang="ta"> māyitaḻ </term> as "black petals", which would be a play on the age-old motif of HER lotus eyes (lotuses, or waterlilies for that matter, do not have black petals like lashes)? Cām. glosses <term xml:lang="ta"> kariya </term> without adding further reflection. Or is it only <term xml:lang="ta"> mā </term> "big" which is intended here? </note> waterlilies.</l>


      </lg>
    </div>
  </body>
</text>
